    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I am fairly firmly against allowing the zero address to be specified.\r\n\r\nCouple of reasons:\r\n\r\n1. It's easy to work around. There are plenty of burn addresses in Ethereum if someone really wants to burn their rewards. More than 1,460,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 of them. Preventing one of them is not a significant limitation. People often use [`0x0000....dead`](https://etherscan.io/address/0x000000000000000000000000000000000000dead) for example.\r\n\r\n2. People sometimes use `0x0000...0000` as a placeholder. Or in automated pipelines, zero can sometimes end up inadvertantly as the value. For example, after the DAO fork, people lost Ether because the UI for the [ReplaySafeSplit](https://etherscan.io/address/0xaa1a6e3e6ef20068f7f8d8c835d2d22fd5116444#code) contract inserted the zero address if the user forgot to specifiy a To address. This is catastrophic UX.\r\n\r\nIf there is a genuine use case for allowing the `0x00` address, I'd be happy to reconsider, but I find it very hard to imagine one.",
